# .gitignore.example — Developer Learning Mode sharing options

# Default (mirrored in .gitignore): knowledge files and config are gitignored.
# Knowledge files contain a learner's mistakes, prior understanding, and revision history.
# That is private learning material by default.
learn/knowledge/
learn/config.json

# --- OPT-IN: Share the team knowledge base ---
#
# If your team wants a shared domain-organized knowledge base that accumulates across
# everyone's sessions, remove the `learn/knowledge/` line above and add
# the inversion pattern below to your real .gitignore.
#
# The config.json remains gitignored even in shared mode — level and focus are
# per-developer preferences, not team state.
#
# !learn/knowledge/
# !learn/knowledge/**
#
# Considerations before opting in:
#   - Knowledge files will contain revision history ("Superseded 2026-05-14: ...") visible to the team.
#   - A junior's foundational entries and a senior's trade-off entries will coexist.
#     That is the point of the layered knowledge base, but the team should be ready for it.
#   - Knowledge files reveal the team's mistakes over time. Psychological safety matters.
